    "summary": "The Destruction of the Second Temple in Jerusalem (70 AD) by the Roman general (later emperor) Titus during the suppression of the First Jewish-Roman War was one of the most consequential events in the history of both Judaism and Christianity. The Temple — rebuilt by Herod the Great and completed shortly before the war — was the center of Jewish religious life, the site of the daily sacrifices, and the focus of Jewish national identity. Its destruction effectively ended Temple Judaism as a living religion and forced a complete reimagining of Jewish practice.\n\nThe Jewish historian Josephus, who witnessed and survived the siege, provides a detailed account in The Jewish War: the Romans breached Jerusalem's walls after a months-long siege, burned the Temple, killed hundreds of thousands, and enslaved the survivors. The Arch of Titus in Rome, still standing, depicts Roman soldiers carrying the Temple's menorah (seven-branched lampstand) in triumph. Rabbinical Judaism, led by sages who reconvened at Yavneh, developed the Torah-study and synagogue-centered tradition that allowed Judaism to survive without a Temple — completing a transformation begun in the Babylonian exile. For Christians, the Temple's destruction was interpreted as fulfillment of Jesus's prediction ('not one stone will be left upon another' — Mark 13:2) and as confirming that the new covenant had superseded the Temple sacrificial system.",
